President Donald Trump and Prime Minister Shinzo Abe of Japan met in New York to discuss recent developments on the Korean Peninsula, including North Korea's commitment to dismantle its weapons of mass destruction and missile programs. They reaffirmed their shared goal of achieving the complete denuclearization of North Korea and emphasized that it is North Korea's responsibility to implement immediate measures in line with its commitment. President Trump thanked Prime Minister Abe for Japan's leadership in enforcing United Nations Security Council resolutions targeting North Korea's maritime activities. Both leaders pledged to work with their ally, South Korea, and other international partners to maintain pressure on North Korea, including urging China and Russia to continue enforcing international sanctions. They also discussed bilateral trade issues and agreed to enter into negotiations for a United States-Japan Trade Agreement, which could have significant economic benefits for both countries. Finally, they expressed their commitment to maintaining a free, open, and prosperous regional order in the Indo-Pacific.